english:
  title: Record of the Old Friend's Pavilion
  author: Pyo Yeon-mal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Twenty miles north of Saneum County lies a valley called Chogok, and at its entrance stands an ancient tree of sacred service. Its roots sprawl across the earth while its branches soar half into the sky, so vast that it can shelter an ox, and its shadow spreads wide enough to shelter a hundred carts. From afar it appears as round as an unfurled parasol, as thick as gathered clouds. All who beheld it marveled at its uncommon majesty.

    The southern provinces harbor many old trees, yet few match this one's dignity. It stands where a vast plain opens southward and a great river winds like a sash—a place that catches the wind abundantly. Last summer, I came to exile in this county and took residence in the home of Song Ki-dong, here in this valley. The sacred tree stood directly before his door. Song-gun, considering my comfort, gathered workers to heap soil beneath it, built stone steps, placed a railing, and set a bamboo bed for sitting and resting, with a thatched shelter nearby to ward off rain and heat. He led me often to rest there, seeking to ease me from the oppressive warmth.

    Observing this tree, I found its branches and leaves so dense that sunlight cannot penetrate, and cool breezes linger of their own accord. Those who sit beneath it grow clear-faced, their hair ruffled by gentle winds. After a time, flesh and bones feel refreshed, the spirit rises buoyant. The weight of sorrow lifts from the belly, the heart's hindrances dissolve. One seems to float free of dust and emerge beyond the thin mists of the world.

    Song-gun's younger brothers and the Pae brothers often came to rest under the tree's shade. We would find village wine and wild provisions, grow merry in drink, and when tired, lay our heads upon the roots to speak of farming and fishing, of clear skies and rainy days. Even when night fell and dew soaked our garments, still we lingered, unwilling to depart. That my exile here brought me peace and I forgot my homeland—this I owe to this tree's grace.

    I have named this place the Old Friend's Pavilion, for this tree offers me what a true friend provides. Though this place lies thousands of miles from the capital, remote and sparsely inhabited, lacking the pleasures of old acquaintances' visits, when I contemplate this tree—its dragon-like trunk, its gnarled branches, its frost-weathered bark clothed in moss—its form seems strange and noble, its bearing stern and grave, as if an elder of virtue stood above, commanding reverence and respect.

    The southern heat and humidity are most severe, the air thick and oppressive as if one could not endure a full day. Yet this tree calls forth the wind through its branches, shakes its leaves to bring coolness. Its rustling sounds like music, its whispers like snow and frost. It is as though I sit with close friends and old companions, my heart laid bare. Then my spirits are stirred: poems take on mournful grace, the zither sounds bright and clear, drunkenness flows freely, sleep comes sweet and pure. Whether I cast stones or read, brew tea or play go, all actions seem touched by ancient simplicity and genuine innocence. The world's dust retreats, and I feel like a figure stepping from an old painting—all through this tree's benediction, as if dwelling with a noble man and receiving the gift of his influence.

    Yet I am fundamentally worthless, discarded by the world, while this tree preserves its natural integrity without seeking use. Thus we seem unrelated, yet I dare call it friend—why? This tree has a gnarled trunk and crooked branches, knotted with many joints, dripping with sap, unsuited for beams or rafters or boats. It is wood of no value, like the rejected elm and oak. Moreover, it did not grow in the central lands but took root in this distant place, unseen by powerful lords, truly useless to the world—much like myself. My nature is rough and unrefined, my learning scattered and incomplete. My spirit disperses, my vital force grows thin. Inside there may be no emptiness, yet outwardly I am only withered. My character is prickly and awkward; I conflict with the world and finally was cast out—truly kindred spirits meeting. Though this tree serves no worldly purpose, it stands majestic and towering, tall beyond reach, serenely invulnerable. Though I fit not with the times, I maintain some grace and solitude without wavering or seeking attachment. Perhaps a gentleman might find something to value in this.

    Ah, though the tree is merely a plant without feeling, having grown old in remote forests and valleys, it now meets me and seems to feel something of true recognition. I too have left my companions and come far, lingering here approaching a full year—can I remain unmoved? Let us seal a pact transcending age differences. Yet something moves me further: the sweetwood tree of the Duke of Shao won the love of the people of its time, while the camphor of Du Fu's cottage could not escape destruction by wind and rain. The sweetwood prospered with its age; the camphor's way was good but its time was dark—their fortunes differed, yet both attained immortal fame.

    This tree, though unprotected by human care, escapes no uprooting calamity; its time may be called auspicious. Yet I lack the wisdom of those great men—how could I secure its eternal remembrance? Should those who come after find my intention worthy and leave this tree unharmed, I would count myself fortunate. Yet one need not make little of what one lacks, nor be prideful of what one possesses. Let us forget the alternation of fortune and misfortune, and entrust all to the natural way.

    Written in the seventh month of the Year of the Pig.
